#Problem 3- probability
integrand1<-function(x){4*(x-11.75)}
#Note we also integrate from -inf to 12 but that equals 0 beacuse f(x) = 0 for anything that is not in the given boundary for f(x)
#firstfunc<-integrate(integrand1,lower = -Inf, upper = 12) = 0
func<-integrate(integrand1,lower = 11.75, upper = 12)
func
0.125 with absolute error < 1.4e-15

Problem 4

probability that variable is larger than 4.5 or smaller than -2.5 mean = 1 standard dev = 1

z =(x - mean)/stdev #using the formula above

P(x > 4.5) = (4.5-1)/1 = 3.5 So we look for the value of 3.0 under 5 in the z norm table = 0.99886 The z score table normally returns for x less than a value but this time around the function is asking for x > 4.5 therefore to get the probability we subtract the value we got from the table from unity = 1-0.99886 = 0.00114

P(X < -2.5) = (-2.5 -1)/1 = -3.5 so we look for the value of -3.0 under 5 in the z norm table = 0.00114 Therefore the probability that variable is larger than 4.5 or less than -2.5 is 0.00114.

Autocorrelations of series x, by lag

#Problem 5b
acf(x,lag.max = 3)

Problem 5b - written answer

From the plot above, since the autocorrelation spike at 1 rises above the dash line, we can say it is significant. However, the autocorrelation is not significant for 2 and 3 since the spikes are not above the dashed lines.

#Problem 8
library(fpp3)
library(ggplot2)
#Box cox transformation for Tobacco in aus_production data of fpp3
#Step 1 is to find lambda
lambda <- aus_production %>%
  features(Tobacco, features = guerrero) %>%
pull(lambda_guerrero)
lambda
[1] 0.9289402
aus_production %>%
  autoplot(box_cox(Tobacco, lambda))

#Problem 9 - Conducting STL decomposition for Canadian Gas data in fpp3
library(fpp3)
canadian_gas %>%
  model(
    STL(Volume ~ trend(window = 7) +    #Volume parameter comes from canadian_gas
          season(window = "periodic"),
        robust = TRUE)) %>%
  components() %>%
  autoplot()
